Windows x86-64 self-hosting platform
----------------------------------------

- Adds `windows-x86_64` to the common JC platform interface and publishes
  compressed `.exe` outputs.
- Adds a compact one-section PE32+ runtime and Juicer launcher with no CRT,
  import library, platform SDK, or host shell dependency.
- Adds `bin/pish.exe` and Windows Orgasm, Juicer, and Concat bootstraps under
  `bin/bootstrap/windows-x86_64/`; no `jc.exe` is checked in.
- Implements the Pith host surface with conditional `kernel32.dll` imports,
  including files, directories, process execution, standard I/O, and
  `VirtualAlloc`-backed memory.
- Makes Pish resolve `.exe` for `$platform == windows-x86_64` and handle drive
  absolute paths.
- Fixes Orgasm conditional preprocessing so nested `%ifdef`, `%ifndef`,
  `%else`, and `%endif` are side-effect free in inactive branches.
- Documents the exact four-executable self-hosting surface for Linux, Windows,
  and FruityOS.

Canonical Linux Pish name and documentation refresh
---------------------------------------------------

- Renames the checked-in Linux Pish bootstrap from `bin/pish.elf` to
  extensionless `bin/pish`, allowing a native Linux shell to run
  `bin/pish build.psh` directly.
- Keeps `bin/pish.fap` as the FruityOS entrypoint; Pish resolves the same
  extensionless command to that file on FruityOS.
- Refreshes repository documentation to match current platform extensions,
  bootstrap placement, source ownership, outputs, and cleaning behavior.

Silent build orchestration and canonical Pish
-----------------------------------------------

- Removes progress-message Echo calls from every build and clean script.
- Keeps the Echo userland utility and its normal build artifacts unchanged.
- Removes Pish from `bin/bootstrap/<platform>/`; canonical `bin/pish` and `bin/pish.fap` are the only checked-in Pish
  executables.

Canonical cross-platform Pish entrypoint
----------------------------------------

- Checks in both `bin/pish` and `bin/pish.fap`; Pish resolves the common
  extensionless command `bin/pish build.psh` through the runtime `$platform`.
- Adds FruityOS bootstrap Orgasm, Juicer, and Concat images under
  `bin/bootstrap/fruityos-x86_64/` alongside the Linux bootstrap set.
- Installs the first `jc`, Orgasm, and Peel tools using the active platform
  extension, allowing the same source tree to bootstrap on Linux or FruityOS.
- Preserves the canonical Pish pair during cleaning while replacing each with
  the freshly built platform counterpart during a build.

Bootstrap tool relocation
-------------------------

- Moves the checked-in Orgasm, Juicer, and Concat executables into
  `bin/bootstrap/<platform>/`.
- Adds stable `bin/{orgasm,juicer,concat}.psh` launchers that dispatch to
  `bin/bootstrap/$platform/<tool>`.
- Installs freshly built host counterparts into `bin/` as soon as each tool is
  available; Pish binary-first lookup then bypasses the launcher automatically.

Unreleased

Build-system changes:

	1. Jabara, Peel, and Yuzu publish executable outputs through
	   rename-<platform>.psh helpers. Linux executables use .elf and FruityOS
	   executables use .fap.
	2. Pish resolves bare executable names using only the extension selected by
	   the runtime $platform value; Linux no longer probes .fap and FruityOS no
	   longer probes .elf.

0.01

Initial release. A monotasking 64 bit OS for x86 written in yuzu: a custom system language.

0.02

This release has mostly involved updates and bugfixes geared toward getting FruityOS
to work on real hardware and to facilitate self-hosting.

Changes:

	1. inode utility which queries inode properties.
	2. harddrive bootloader is now the prefered bootloader. Also works on HDD emulated USB.
	3. the creat syscall will now overwrite existing file.
	4. image now contains userland sources and a script to build them.
	5. fapld has been removed from the repository.
	6. userland code can now use int 0x84 to make kernel calls.
	7. pie shell (pish) is now part of the kernel.
	8. getch syscall is now non-blocking. returns -1 if fail.
	9. IDT is now initialized in the kernel rather than the bootloader and added many isrs.
	10. memory map has changed and more memory is available for the application heap.
	11. /init.psh script is now executed on boot.

Bugfixes:

	1. bootloader memory corruption bug (2bf356a)
	2. inode_unlink memory corruption bug (b020853, 76a3168)
	3. idt not working on real hardware or anything but qemu (50b0570)

Notes:

	Required RAM is now 16 MB.

0.03

FruityOS 0.03 completes the transition to the Jabara toolchain and adds a
native UEFI boot path, reproducible source packaging, and an on-system userland
rebuild.

Changes:

	1. Pulp and Peel now build with the self-hosted Jabara compiler.
	2. Orgasm provides a Jabara-written, Zest-compatible assembler for every
	   instruction and directive required by FruityOS.
	3. The build produces legacy BIOS, standalone PE32+ EFI, and FAT16 UEFI
	   disk images.
	4. Every image contains a Jar- and Juicer-packaged snapshot of the current
	   source worktree.
	5. Startup extracts the checkout, rebuilds sixteen userland applications
	   natively, and installs them into /bin.
	6. The initrd contains only nine host-built FAP files plus host-generated
	   Jabara compiler assembly required to run the native build.
	7. RAMFS inode names now support 63 characters, preserving generated source
	   filenames.
	8. Kernel heap and application mappings were expanded for the native
	   compiler workflow.
	9. Documentation is organized as a concise project overview and detailed
	   guides under docs/.

Bugfixes:

	1. PE32+ sections, relocation metadata, memory-map handling, and firmware
	   handoff were hardened for physical UEFI implementations.
	2. BIOS startup now delays interrupts until the initrd has been copied out
	   of the boot-image buffer, preventing IST-stack corruption.
	3. QEMU run scripts use temporary image copies, avoiding stale write locks
	   and accidental modification of release artifacts.
	4. Orgasm now handles the byte operations, nested expressions, memory
	   operands, and descriptor data used by Pulp and generated FAP assembly.
	5. Native compilation no longer loses source files with long names or
	   exhausts the original RAMFS data pool.

Notes:

	Secure Boot is not supported. Physical UEFI systems must disable it or use
	a locally signed fruityos.efi. VGA-compatible text output and PS/2 keyboard
	input are still required after firmware handoff.

0.04

FruityOS 0.04 completes the source-built native toolchain, reduces the binary
bootstrap, and makes every boot image consume the same initrd layout.

Changes:

	1. FruityOS now rebuilds the Jabara compiler, Orgasm, all Peel applications,
	   and Pulp from the packaged source tree before presenting the shell prompt.
	   Every FAP left in /bin has therefore been compiled from source during boot.
	2. Jabara has one implicit, headerless module output and accepts multiple
	   source inputs. ELF and FAP origins, headers, entry points, allocators, and
	   runtimes are selected explicitly during assembly.
	3. Orgasm has no output modes and accepts multiple assembly inputs with one
	   shared symbol table. ELF files use an explicit org directive and a manual
	   assembly header; Orgasm's special ELF writer has been removed.
	4. The host bootstrap uses NASM only to assemble the initial Orgasm executable
	   and the Seed bootloaders. Orgasm assembles jc, compatibility tools,
	   userland applications, and Pulp.
	5. Native Pulp is compiled from one multifile Jabara module, assembled from
	   the generated module plus handwritten entry and IDT assembly, and
	   compressed to pulp.sys with Juicer.
	6. The initrd binary bootstrap has been reduced to four FAPs: jar, juicer,
	   orgasm, and pish. FruityOS assembles the initial jc and builds del from its
	   Jabara source before removing temporary archives and intermediates.
	7. fruityos.jz contains an explicit minimal rebuild manifest rather than a
	   repository snapshot. Documentation, host shell scripts, tests,
	   compatibility sources, bootloader sources, and unrelated files are
	   excluded.
	8. All Seed variants locate /pulp.sys as an ordinary initrd Jar entry instead
	   of relying on a separate kernel stream or deterministic archive ordering.
	9. Native .psh sources are centralized under scripts/ and copied to their
	   expected component paths only while fruityos.jz is staged.
	10. Final BIOS, floppy, UEFI disk, and standalone EFI artifacts are written
	    below bin/. One launcher selects uefi, hdd, or fd and always boots a
	    temporary image copy.
	11. Pulp prints "Booting..." once its global console is available, before
	    startup extracts and builds the packaged checkout.

Bugfixes:

	1. Nested Pish invocations no longer fault while running component build
	   scripts.
	2. UEFI reserves the kernel, paging, heap, and stable initrd regions before
	   ExitBootServices, preventing firmware allocations from corrupting Pulp.
	3. PIC initialization now belongs to Pulp, so BIOS, floppy, and UEFI Seed
	   variants enter the kernel with consistent interrupt routing.
	4. BIOS, floppy, and UEFI loaders scan Jar records for pulp.sys instead of
	   assuming it is the first entry. The floppy load window was expanded to
	   accommodate the source-complete initrd while staying below firmware data.
	5. Large native compiler and assembler inputs no longer require concat or
	   per-part compiler modes, and Orgasm releases each input buffer between
	   files.
	6. Native build intermediates are removed as soon as source-built del becomes
	   available, keeping peak RAMFS use within the fixed-block heap.

Notes:

	The rebuilt Pulp artifacts remain in RAMFS and do not replace the kernel
	that is currently running. Secure Boot and the VGA/PS2 hardware requirements
	remain unchanged from 0.03.

Stage-0 DOS bootstrap:
- Added the 254-byte, platform-blind Petit DOS assembler.
- Added readable Petit sources for the uncompressed Linux and Windows
  Orgasm bootstrap executables.
- Added the authoritative generated jbc.asm to stage0.
- Added DOS batch scripts that materialize stage-0 outputs under bin/.

Stage 0 naming and documentation
--------------------------------

- Renamed the stage-0 assembler and source to `stage0/petit.com` and
  `stage0/petit.pm`.
- Added a complete Petit language and implementation manual covering syntax,
  symbol/fixup chains, memory layout, limits, self-reproduction, and DOS use.
- Preserved the authoritative Jabara source tree under `jabara/src/`.
